[The number of countries and territories reporting confirmed cases of COVID-19 to WHO remains at 215.

In the 24 hours since the last WHO update:
-----------------------------------------
The Americas region reported 59.5% of the global newly reported cases and 65.3% of newly reported deaths for this 24-hour period. Brazil reported 38.2% of the newly confirmed cases in the region, the USA reported 35.7%, Chile 6.2%, Mexico 5.2%, and Peru 3.8%. The same 5 countries remained at the top, with the same ordering.

The European region reported 10.6% of the global newly reported cases and 7.0% of the newly confirmed deaths in the region. Russia reported 47.0% of the regional newly reported cases, followed by the UK 7.6%, Turkey 7.4%, Ukraine 4.2%, Belarus 3.5%, and Germany 3.3%. Again, same countries, minor juggling of orders and percentages day by day (Germany and Belarus switched places again).

The Eastern Mediterranean region reported 11.2% of the global newly reported cases and 11.3% of global newly reported fatalities. Pakistan reported 26.1% of the regional newly reported cases followed by Saudi Arabia 19.7%, Iran 13.8%, Iraq 9.6%, Egypt 8.6%, Oman 5.3%, and Qatar 5.1%. Same countries, minor juggling of positions (Oman and Qatar switched places).

The African region reported 5.0% of the global newly reported cases and 3.0% of newly reported fatalities. South Africa reported 60.2% of the newly reported cases in the region in the past 24 hours, followed by Cameroon 8.4%, Nigeria and Ghana 5.7%, each, Kenya 3.4%, and Cote d'Ivoire 2.8%. While South Africa and Nigeria are consistently numbers 1 and 2 in terms of the 24-hour increase in cases, other countries have less consistent reporting patterns and vary considerably from day to day.

The Western Pacific region reported 0.69% of the global newly reported cases and 0.47% of global deaths. The Philippines reported 62.0% of the newly reported cases in the region, followed by Singapore 24.9%, Japan 4.9%, Australia 2.4%, and China 2.0%. The outbreak associated with the Beijing Seafood markets continues to bring China to prominence in terms of daily newly confirmed cases. That said, the Philippines and Singapore are consistently numbers 1 and 2, respectively, and the other countries, including Malaysia and Australia, vary in daily reporting.

The South East Asia region reported 12.9% of the global newly reported cases and 12.9% of global deaths. India reported 75.4% of newly reported cases in the region, followed by Bangladesh 18.0%, Indonesia 4.4%, and Nepal 2.1%. Same countries, same order as in previous days, with India continuing to be the driving force in the regional growth in cases.

Impression: Europe seems to be stabilizing at a significantly lower rate, although Russia is still reporting 7000+ new cases a day (down from 8000+ per day). The Eastern Mediterranean has surpassed the European region, with Pakistan reporting around 4000+ cases a day and Saudi Arabia reporting around 4000+ cases a day. South East Asia has overtaken both the European and Eastern Mediterranean regions, with India reporting 8000-10 000+ cases a day (over 14 000 cases today 22 Jun 2020). The Americas region is usually reporting around 70 000 cases a day (over 90 000 cases today 22 Jun 2020), with Brazil usually reporting 25 000-30 000+ cases a day (over 34 000 cases today 22 Jun 2020) and the USA at 20 000-25 000+ a day (over 32 000 today 22 Jun 2020). In the Africa region, the regional proportion is slowly climbing, with South Africa reporting in the 3000-4000+ range daily, and the Western Pacific region is maintaining a very low rate compared with the other regions, with the Philippines averaging 500+ cases per day (over 600 cases today 22 Jun 2020). (Singapore had been reporting twice as many cases per day for a period of time but has dropped back over the past couple of weeks).

Figure 2. Epidemic curve of confirmed COVID-19 cases, by date of report and WHO region, 30 Dec 2019 through 22 Jun 2020, at the source URL above, is an excellent representation of the epidemic starting in the Western Pacific, transitioning to multiregional activity as the virus travelled. Europe has significantly decreased. The Americas region continues to increase, as does South East Asia, in terms of daily newly confirmed cases; the African region is noticeably increasing as well. The Americas region continues to greatly outnumber all other regions for daily reporting. - Mod.MPP]

